Polar representation of complex numbers
If \(r\) is the modulus and \(\theta\) the argument of \(z = x + iy\), then \[
    \left\{
        \begin{array}{l}
        x = r \cos \theta \\
        y = r \sin\theta
        \end{array}
    \right.
\]
This gives us the polar representation of \(z\): \[\begin{align*}
    z & = x + iy \\
      & = \boxed{r( \cos \theta + i \sin \theta) }
\end{align*}\]

Periodicity of sine and cosine



Sine and cosine are \(2\pi\)-periodic: \[
  \boxed{
      \begin{align*}
          \sin(\theta \pm 2 \pi) & = \sin \theta \\
          \cos(\theta \pm 2 \pi) & = \cos \theta
      \end{align*}}
\]
The tangent is \(\pi\)-periodic: \[
  \boxed{
      \begin{align*}
          \tan(\theta \pm \pi) & = \tan \theta
      \end{align*}}
\]

Example: Compute \(\displaystyle \tan\left(\frac{8093 \pi}{4}\right)\)

Example
If we divide \(x^2 + 1\) by \(x - 1\), we get:
\[\begin{align*}
    \frac{x^2 + 1}{x - 1}
        & = \frac{x^2 -1 + 2}{x - 1} \\
        & = \frac{x^2 - 1}{x - 1} + \frac{2}{x - 1} \\
        & = x + 1 + \frac{2}{x - 1}
\end{align*}\]
Therefore, the quotient is \(Q(x) = x + 1\) and the remainder is \(R(x) = 2\).

Reflection across the \(x\)-axis (even/odd identities)


\[
    \boxed{
        \begin{align*}
            \cos(-\theta) & = \phantom{-} \cos \theta \\
            \sin(-\theta) & = - \sin \theta \\
        \end{align*}}
\]
Example: Compute \(\sin(-\pi/4)\)

Reflection across the \(y\)-axis (complementary angles)


\[
    \boxed{
        \begin{align*}
            \cos(\pi - \theta) & = - \cos\theta \\
            \sin(\pi - \theta) & = \phantom{-} \sin \theta
        \end{align*}}
\]

Shift formulas (by \(\pi\))


\[
    \boxed{
        \begin{align*}
            \cos(\pi + \theta) & = - \cos \theta \\
            \sin(\pi + \theta) & = - \sin \theta \\
            \tan(\pi + \theta) & = \phantom{-} \tan\theta
        \end{align*}}
\]

Addition/subtraction formulas (for \(\tan\))
\[
    \boxed{
        \begin{align*}
            \tan(\alpha + \beta) & = \frac{\tan \alpha + \tan \beta}{1 - \tan \alpha \tan \beta} \\
            \tan(\alpha - \beta) & = \frac{\tan \alpha - \tan \beta}{1 + \tan \alpha \tan \beta}
        \end{align*}}
\]

Double-angle formulas (\(2\theta \to \theta\))
\[
    \boxed{
        \begin{align*}
            \sin(2 \theta) & = 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta \\
            \cos(2 \theta) & = \cos^2 \theta - \sin^2 \theta \\
            \tan(2 \theta) & = \frac{2 \tan \theta}{1 - \tan^2 \theta}
        \end{align*}}
\]

Follows from the addition/subtraction formulas.
The double-angle formula for \(\cos\) can also be written as

\[
    \boxed{
        \begin{align*}
            \cos(2 \theta) & = \cos^2 \theta - \sin^2 \theta \\
                           & = 2 \cos^2 \theta - 1 \\
                           & = 1 - 2 \sin^2 \theta
        \end{align*}}
\]

Half-angle formulas (\(\theta \to 2\theta\))
\[
    \boxed{
        \begin{align*}
            \cos^2 \theta & = \frac{1 + \cos(2\theta)}{2} \\
            \sin^2 \theta & = \frac{1 - \cos(2\theta)}{2} \\            
            \tan^2 \theta & = \frac{1 - \cos(2\theta)}{1 + \cos(2\theta)}
        \end{align*}}
\]

These formulas are useful to compute integrals of powers of \(\sin\) and \(\cos\).

Product-to-sum formulas
\[
    \boxed{
        \begin{align*}
            \sin \alpha \cos \beta & = \frac{1}{2}(\sin(\alpha + \beta) + \sin(\alpha - \beta)) \\
            \cos \alpha \sin \beta & = \frac{1}{2}(\sin(\alpha + \beta) - \sin(\alpha - \beta)) \\
            \cos \alpha \cos \beta & = \frac{1}{2}(\cos(\alpha + \beta) + \cos(\alpha - \beta) \\
            \sin \alpha \sin \beta & = \frac{1}{2}(\cos(\alpha - \beta) - \cos(\alpha + \beta)
    \end{align*}}
\]

Sum-to-product formulas
\[
    \boxed{
        \begin{align*}
            \sin \alpha + \sin \beta & = \phantom{-} 2\sin\left(\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}\right) \cos\left(\frac{\alpha-\beta}{2}\right) \\
            \sin \alpha - \sin \beta & = \phantom{-} 2\cos\left(\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}\right) \sin\left(\frac{\alpha-\beta}{2}\right) \\            
            \cos \alpha + \cos \beta & = \phantom{-} 2\cos\left(\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}\right) \cos\left(\frac{\alpha-\beta}{2}\right) \\
            \cos \alpha - \cos \beta & = - 2\sin\left(\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}\right) \sin\left(\frac{\alpha-\beta}{2}\right)
        \end{align*}}
\]

Derivatives of trigonometric functions
\[\begin{align*}
    \frac{d}{dx} \sin x & = \cos x \\
    \frac{d}{dx} \cos x & = - \sin x \\
    \frac{d}{dx} \tan x & = \frac{1}{\cos^2 x}
\end{align*}\]
